The most recent opcode added was OP_CHECKSIGADD with the Taproot upgrade in 2021. 

Read our full report: Developers of Bitcoin https://t.co/miIRuzsRQU

By tracking the number of opcodes through successive Bitcoin Core versions, we see that developers initially reduced functions that were deemed to be unsafe and have gradually been adding features since.
While Bitcoin Core is coded in C++, its operation relies on something called Script, a simple programming language that allows for validation of transactions on the network.

To that end, Bitcoin developers actually removed features in its earliest days in the name of security and have only cautiously added new features since. One way of tracking the complexity of the Bitcoin network is through something called opcodes.

From its insistence on backward-compatible upgrades to the way the developer community comes to agreement on decisions, Bitcoin has focused on being an electronic payment and store of-value system for the digital age.

The development of Bitcoin, while itself an original concept, has generally favored security and safety over technical novelty and flexibility, especially relative to other blockchains. üßµ https://t.co/lY8BQdvx4A
